Step Four: Implement Multi-Touch Engagement Strategy
Prospects don't convert from single touchpoint. They need multiple interactions across multiple channels before buying decision solidifies. Yet most organizations default to single email or call, then move on.

Targeted lead engagement requires multi-touch approach. Email initiates contact, establishes credibility, communicates value proposition. If prospect doesn't respond to email, follow-up call engages differently. If email and call don't convert, content reinforces messaging. If prospect shows interest, more frequent engagement accelerates buying journey.

Different channels serve different purposes. Email reaches broad audience efficiently. Phone calls create personal connection. Content demonstrates expertise. Social engagement builds familiarity. Direct mail stands out from digital saturation. Webinars educate and assess fit.

Orchestrate these channels strategically. Don't bombard with random touchpoints. Create sequences where each builds on previous. First email introduces you and value proposition. Follow-up call adds personal dimension. Content addresses specific objection from first call. Another email references content they downloaded. This sequencing creates momentum.

Timing matters. Spacing touchpoints too far apart allows prospect to forget you. Spacing too close feels aggressive. Most B2B buying involves 5-7 meaningful interactions before decision. Orchestrate these interactions across weeks with appropriate spacing.

Personalization matters too. Generic mass emails get ignored. Emails referencing their specific company, industry, documented challenges get opened and read. Personalization signals respect and increases response probability.

Step Five: Qualify Leads Using Clear Criteria
Not all leads matching your profile are sales qualified. Some lack budget. Some lack authority. Some aren't ready to buy. Some are evaluating out of curiosity rather than actual need. You need systematic qualification to separate real opportunities from time-wasters.

Establish clear qualification criteria. Common framework uses BANT: Budget available, Authority to decide, Need for your solution, Timing of decision. Leads lacking any of these components typically don't convert.

But BANT isn't comprehensive enough alone. Add behavioral indicators: Do they engage with your content? Do they download resources? Do they attend webinars? Do they respond to outreach? Engagement signals intent.

Add intent indicators: Are they researching solutions? Are they visiting competitor websites? Are they discussing budget allocation? Did they recently hire relevant staff or announce relevant initiatives? Intent signals show active buying process.

Document your full qualification framework. Make it clear what sales considers qualified versus unqualified. Establish handoff criteria between marketing and sales. Ensure both functions share understanding of what qualified means.

Then enforce qualification discipline. Marketing shouldn't push unqualified leads into sales pipeline hoping something converts. Sales shouldn't accept every lead marketing passes, validating poor lead quality. Clear standards with enforcement create alignment.

